<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOSEMITE CLIMB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I would like to thank The Times and staff writer Clay Evans for the excellent 
coverage of Mark Wellman's courageous climb to be the first paraplegic to scale 
Yosemite's 3,200-foot El Capitan. 
</P>
<P>
Having known Mark for several years, there is much more to add to this personal 
triumph of the human spirit than the world knows. And the world should know. 
</P>
<P>
Once told by doctors he would never lead any kind of "normal" or "active" life 
after his tragic climbing accident in 1982, Mark has continuously proven his 
critics wrong. For he is not the least bit handicapped, but on the contrary, he 
is much more active than most normal people. Besides being a year-round park 
ranger, he's a nationally ranked wheelchair tennis player, and intermediate 
kayaker, an avid swimmer (using buoyants to keep his legs afloat), rides a 
specialized "bike" that he operates with his arms, while also heading 
Yosemite's handicapped skiing program at Badger Pass. 
</P>
<P>
Yes, he's a great athlete, a great inspiration. But most of all, he's a great 
friend. SuperGimp, we're proud of you! Now the whole world knows. 
</P>
<P>
TARIK M. TRAD 
</P>
<P>
Montclair 
</P>
</TEXT>
