<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANTONOVICH CALLS FOR COMPROMISE ON WETLANDS; 
</P>
<P>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS, LANDOWNERS AT ODDS ON DEVELOPMENT PLAN FOR DESERT OASIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SEBASTIAN ROTELLA, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles County Supervisor Mike Antonovich said Wednesday that he hopes a 
wetlands area near Palmdale that has been the subject of a debate over proposed 
development can be protected because of its archeological and biological value. 
</P>
<P>
Antonovich toured the Barrel Springs wetlands in the Antelope Valley with 
residents who oppose a plan to build 8 homes on the 63-acre county parcel on 
the edge of Palmdale between Avenue T-8 and the California Aqueduct. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a very valid issue," Antonovich said. "Because of the archeological 
significance, this area could be a learning center for young people from 
kindergarten all the way up through community college." 
</P>
<P>
Antonovich and his staff members said the supervisor is not taking sides in the 
dispute. Antonovich said that he hopes local activists, government agencies and 
the landowners, Stanley and Lois Sevilla, can fashion a compromise, and said 
that state parkland or education funds might be available for preservation of 
the area. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Biological Study 
</P>
<P>
Last month, the county Regional Planning Commission instructed Sevilla to 
commission a biological study of wildlife in the wetlands, delaying until 
October the appeal of a hearing officer's approval of the construction 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
State and federal environmental officials have urged stringent restrictions on 
development of the Barrel Springs area because it is a rare oasis in the 
desert. It has been a hub of human activity for thousands of years, yielding 
the earliest archeological evidence of human presence in the Antelope Valley 
and a wealth of Indian artifacts. 
</P>
<P>
Antonovich's comments were praised by Jim McAvoy, president of the North Los 
Angeles County Coalition for Planned Growth and Responsive Government, who 
arranged the 5th District supervisor's tour. "I think he seemed genuinely 
interested," McAvoy said. "I believe he recognized the uniqueness of the area 
and the fact that it's worth saving." 
</P>
<P>
Also touring the area was Antelope Valley Community College President Allan 
Kurki, who said he is interested in preserving the area because of its 
potential educational value. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Low Density 
</P>
<P>
While the landowner has said his low-density development would not harm the 
natural resources of the area, McAvoy said even minimal development would be 
ecologically devastating. He and others want the county to acquire the property 
and designate it an environmentally protected area. 
</P>
<P>
The dispute could come to the Board of Supervisors if either side appeals the 
eventual decision by the Regional Planning Commission. But before the 
commission reviews the case Oct. 11, Antonovich suggested compromises, such as 
clustering the proposed homes away from wetland areas, or obtaining county 
approval to transfer the proposed housing to a 118-acre site south of the 
California Aqueduct, the southern boundary of the Sevillas' property. 
</P>
<P>
But Lois Sevilla said Wednesday that moving the project is impossible because 
she and her husband have already sold the land they owned south of the 
aqueduct. 
</P>
<P>
"It has been our feeling all along that the development could be done 
consistently with ecological values," she said. "That's why it's low density. 
We are surprised that we're getting this kind of response." 
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Palmdale City Council and Planning Commission will 
hold a joint meeting Tuesday to discuss possible methods of preserving the 
wetlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
