<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Energy Department delayed efforts to stop radioactive wastes from 
contaminating ground water near its Hanford, Wash., nuclear weapons plant so 
that production could continue, a congressional study found. The report from 
the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress, disputed 
Energy Department assertions that the leakage of an estimated 750,000 gallons 
of toxic wastes from the plant's underground storage tanks would have little 
impact on the nearby Columbia River. The GAO said although it was learned in 
1956 that some single-walled tanks at Hanford might be leaking, those tanks 
were still being used in 1980. DOE officials said that liquids were kept below 
the leaky spots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
