<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE STATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For the first time, California raisins are headed for store shelves in Japan, 
with the first shipment of about $1.5 million worth of the fruit leaving the 
Port of Oakland. The raisins are being exported by the California Dried Fruit 
Co., a consortium of 18 San Joaquin Valley companies. Nicholas Boghosian, 
president of the consortium, said the sale of bulk raisins to Japan culminates 
four years of negotiations. He said the company has also developed packaging 
and advertising to meet Japanese standards and has licensed Japanese importers 
and distributors to use the California dancing raisins logo on all packages and 
in television commercials in Japan. If raisins are a hit with Japanese 
consumers, Boghosian said he hopes that the consortium can increase shipments 
in future years. 
</P>
