<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEUKMEJIAN MOROCCO-BOUND FOR A PARTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARL INGRAM, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gov. George Deukmejian, hardly anyone's definition of a party boy, will shuck 
convention and join the jet set next week for a high-power, celebrity studded 
birthday celebration in Tangier for publisher Malcolm Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
A bit out of the ordinary for the strait-laced governor who celebrates 
political victories with a heaping bowl of jamoca almond fudge ice cream, you 
may wonder? 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps a bit, conceded press secretary Kevin Brett. He confirmed that 
Deukmejian and his wife, Gloria, will join about 800 special friends Aug. 19 to 
celebrate Forbes' 70th birthday at the magazine publisher's castle overlooking 
the Mediterranean. 
</P>
<P>
"This may not be what people normally associate with George Deukmejian," Brett 
said. But he quickly added: "They should understand it is not unlike Gov. 
Deukmejian to meet with highly visible . . . individuals in the business 
community, albeit in a social setting." 
</P>
<P>
According to a Washington Post society column, invited guests include such 
personalities as Elizabeth Taylor; Chrysler Corp. chairman Lee Iacocca; 
television's Barbara Walters and Walter Cronkite; actress Dina Merrill; 
designer Oscar de la Renta; Fiat chairman Giovanni Agnelli; Washington Post 
chairman Katherine Graham; comedienne Joan Rivers and former Treasury Secretary 
W. Michael Blumenthal. 
</P>
<P>
Deukmejian and the governor of Rhode Island, Ed DiPrete, are believed to be the 
only two political officeholders to attend, Brett said. He noted that the 
Deukmejians' costs, including round-trip chartered jet fare from New York to 
Morocco, will be paid by Forbes and reported on the governor's legally required 
disclosure of gifts report. 
</P>
<P>
Brett said Deukmejian, who is accompanied at virtually every function by at 
least one staff aide, would not have office assistants on this trip. "I cannot 
think of a similar situation where that has occurred," Brett said. 
</P>
<P>
The press secretary refused to discuss how Deukmejian's name got on the guest 
list, but he said "there is a familiarity with Gov. Deukmejian by Malcolm 
Forbes himself." He noted that the governor's picture was on the cover of 
Forbes magazine in 1984 and the publication printed a story about his program 
to balance the state budget. Since then, the governor has met with the 
magazine's staff, Brett said. 
</P>
<P>
Brett said the Morocco trip will be sandwiched between long-scheduled official 
state business conferences Deukmejian will hold with bankers, investors and 
corporate executives in New York Aug. 16-22. 
</P>
<P>
He said Deukmejian, as he has in the past, would meet with the finance 
executives to discuss the fiscal condition of California and seek to attract 
more investment in the state. 
</P>
<P>
Deukmejian will fly to New York on Wednesday, meet with manufacturing 
executives on Thursday, fly to Morocco on Friday, party on Saturday, return to 
New York on Sunday, hold more conferences on Monday and return to California on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
DEUKMEJIAN, GEORGE; PARTIES; MOROCCO -- CELEBRATIONS; FORBES, MALCOM JR; 
JUNKETS; CELEBRITIES; MEETINGS; CALIFORNIA -- FINANCES 
</P>
