<HEADLINE>
<P>
USC EXTENDS ITS REACH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRUCE KEPPEL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The University of Southern California is wiring itself for the 21st Century as 
a crew from American Telephone &amp; Telegraph installs a new 
telecommunications nerve center. The so-called Integrated Services Digital 
Network, or ISDN, will enable faculty and researchers to communicate with 
colleagues around the world over a system that carries voice, pictures and 
computer data simultaneously over the same telephone line. 
</P>
<P>
"USC is part of a worldwide research community," said spokesman Hugh Kelley. 
"We have a tremendous interaction with other countries and other organizations 
worldwide." 
</P>
<P>
Under a $23-million contract, AT&amp;T also is delivering 10,000 telephone sets 
(3,000 of them ISDN-compatible), a network management system, a microwave radio 
link, fiber-optic and coaxial cables and three equipment rooms as well as 
maintenance service. 
</P>
<P>
When the new system starts operating in the fall, USC will join the 
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and North Carolina's Duke University as 
the only U.S. institutions of higher learning with ISDN technology. BRUCE 
KEPPEL 
</P>
</TEXT>
